def time_series_plot(dataframe, y_col):
    """
    Create a time series plot
    
    Parameters:
    dataframe: dataframe 
    y_col: target column of a dataframe to be displayed

    Return:
    a time series plot with additive trend as seasonal decomposition using moving averages
    """
    dataframe = dataframe.set_index('Date')
    sd = seasonal_decompose(dataframe[[y_col]], model = 'additive')
    plt.figure(figsize = (30, 6))
    plt.plot(dataframe[[y_col]], color = 'green', label = y_col)
    plt.plot(sd.trend, color = 'black', label = 'additive trend')
    plt.xticks(dataframe[[y_col]].index[::12], rotation = 45)
    plt.title(y_col)
    plt.legend()

def decompose_time_series(series, frequency):
    """
    Decompose a time series by given frequency
    
    Parameters:
    series: an array of data series
    frequency: target column of a dataframe to be displayed

    Return:
    a seasonal decomposition of time series additive trend as seasonal decomposition
    """
    mpl.style.use('seaborn')
    result = seasonal_decompose(series, model = 'additive', period = frequency)
    result.plot()

def train_test_split(data, date_filter):
    """
    Split data into train and test datasets by date_filter
    
    Parameters:
    data: input dataframe
    date_filter: the date to be split train and test sets

    Return:
    a training and testing datasets split by given date
    """
    training = data[data.Date < date_filter]
    testing = data[data.Date >= date_filter ]
    return training, testing

With the underlying statistical assumptions,the Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average (ARIMA) model provides a good starting point in time series forecasting. It is a linear combination of Auto-Regressive (lag(s) of target variable) AR terms, Moving Averages (lag(s) of forecast errors) MA terms and differencing I term, when the process is non-stationary. The parameters p, d, q in the ARIMA(p, d, q) model are:

  • p: the number of autoregressive terms
  • d: the number of differencing
  • q: the number of lagged forecast error terms

Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) is used to estimate the quality of each ARIMA model relative to each of other models, which provides a means for model selection. AIC is calcuated from the number of independent variables used to build the model, and the maximum likelihood estimate of the model, that is how well the model reproduces the data. The best-fit ARIMA model according to AIC is the one which explains the greatest amount of variation using the fewest possible independent variables. Therefore the lower the AIC value, the better the model.

In [69]:
# determine the necessity of time differencing using Augmented Dickey-Fuller unit root test
adf_test_result = adfuller(df_agg_date["Sales"])
print('ADF Statistic: %f' % adf_test_result[0])
print('p-value: %f' % adf_test_result[1])
print('Critical Values:')
for key, value in adf_test_result[4].items():
  print('\t%s: %.3f' % (key, value))

ADF Statistic: -2.685905
p-value: 0.076509
Critical Values:
	1%: -3.440
	5%: -2.866
	10%: -2.569

Since the p-value 0.0765 is between 0.05 and 0.1, the ADF Statistic -2.686 is closer to Critical Values at 10% (-2.569). The Null-hypothesis of ADF-test that the process has an unit root can be rejected at 10% confidence level, therefore the process is stationary and time differencing for stationarity is NOT necessary.

In [ ]:
def best_arima_by_aic(dataframe, tar_var, exog_var):    
    """
    automatically determine parameters of ARIMA model
    
    Parameters:
    dataframe: input dataframe
    tar_var: target variable of input dataframe
    exog_var: exogenous variable(s) of input dataframe

    Return:
    best parameters p and q of ARIMA model by least aic values
    """
    best_aic = 1000000 # initiate a very large best_aic value
    for p in range(8): 
        for q in range(8):
            model = ARIMA(dataframe[tar_var], order = (p, 0, q), exog = dataframe[exog_var]) # stationary process: d = 0
            model_fit = model.fit()
            print("p: ", p, "q: ", q, "; AIC: ", model_fit.aic)
            if model_fit.aic < best_aic:
                best_aic = model_fit.aic
                best_model = model_fit
                best_p = p
                best_q = q
    return best_p, best_q

# based on the automatic determination of parameters in ARIMA model to implement forecasting model by rolling the training periods
def rolling_forecasting_result(step, training, testing, target_var):
    """
    apply the rolling ARIMA model results on next element of test set
    
    Parameters: 
    step: period between training and testing datasets
    training: initial input training dataset used for training
    testing: initial input testing dataset used for testing
    target_var: input target variable

    Return:
    df and summary as model and business evaluation metrics
    """
    train_series = pd.Series.tolist(training[target_var])
    test_series = pd.Series.tolist(testing[target_var])
    time_series = pd.Series.tolist(testing.Date)
    predictions = list()
    dt = []
    for t in range(len(test_series)):
        model = ARIMA(train_series, order = (7, 0, 7)) # exog variables were not applied due to memory runout
        model_fit = model.fit()
        output = model_fit.forecast()
        yhat = output[0]
        predictions.append(yhat)
        obs = test_series[t - step]
        train_series.append(obs)
        dt.append([time_series[t], 
                   yhat,
                   test_series[t],
                  test_series[t] - yhat,
                  1 - abs(test_series[t] - yhat)/test_series[t],
                  (test_series[t] - yhat)/abs(test_series[t] - yhat),
                  abs(test_series[t] - yhat)/test_series[t]])
        df = pd.DataFrame(dt)
        df.columns = ['Date', 'Sales_Forecast', 'Actual_Sales', 'Forecast_Error', 'Forecast_Accuracy', 'Tracking_Signal', 'Error_Ratio']
    bias = df[['Forecast_Error']].mean()
    tracking_signal = df[['Tracking_Signal']].sum()
    mae = abs(df[['Forecast_Error']]).mean()
    mape = df[['Error_Ratio']].mean()
    mse = mean_squared_error(test_series, predictions)
    rmse = sqrt(mean_squared_error(test_series, predictions))
    summary = {'bias': bias,
               'sum_tracking_signal': tracking_signal,
               'mean_average_error': mae,
               'mean_average_percentage_error': mape,
               'mean_square_error': mse,
               'root_mean_square_error': rmse}
    return df, summary

def plot_forecast_vs_actual(tbl):
    """
    visualise a forecast again actual sales
    
    Parameters:
    tbl: input test dataset

    Return:
    time series Sales Forecast against Actual Sales
    """
    tbl = tbl.set_index('Date')
    plt.figure(figsize = (30, 6))
    mpl.style.use('seaborn')

    plt.plot(tbl[['Actual_Sales']],'-g', label = 'Actual Sales')
    plt.plot(tbl[['Sales_Forecast']],'-r', label='Sales Forecast')
    plt.xticks(tbl.index[::2], rotation = 45)
    plt.title('Sales Forecast vs Actual Sales')

    plt.legend()

3) Conclusion & Business Insights¶

The following KPIs are used in the forecast evaluation. For each single day in the test set,

  • Forecast Error measures how the forecast sales deviated from actual sales.
  • Forecast Accuracy tells how accurate sales has been forecasted. The better the forecast accuracy, the more aligned the operational costs are and the higher the profits.
  • Tracking Signal measures the existence of persistent bias. For one period it is either 1 which indicates under-forecasting (actual sales is higher than forecast) or -1 which indicates over-forecasting (actual sales is lower than forecasting).
  • Error Ratio measures how inaccurate the sales has been forecasted.

Forecast Accuracy will be the main KPI to monitor the business performance based on the forecast model. The Forecast Accuracy of forecast with cold-start is around 70-80%. 90% is considered to be a good forecast.

In this forecasting exercise - Sales Forecast per day, Forecast Accuracy is on average 84%. As observed graphically the peaks between 2014-05-24 and 2014-05-26 and the dip on 2014-05-27 were not captured in the model, which reduce the forecast accuracy. This should be targeted as the next improvement trial.

As a summary of forecast across all observations in a test period,

  • bias is measured as mean forecast error, shows the tendency for forecast errors to trend in one direction.
  • sum_tracking_signal indicates the overall existence of persistent bias.
  • mean_average_error measures forecast accuracy by averaging the magnitudes of the forecast errors and thereby revealing the variability of forecasts over time.
  • mean_average_percentage_error expresses the degree of error as a percentage.
  • mean_square_error evaluates forecast performance by averaging the squares of the forecast errors, which removes all negative terms.
  • root_mean_square_error is defined as the square root of the average squared error, which gives the same unit in comparison to mean square error.

In this forecasting exercise, the over tracking signal is negative, which indicates there is an over-forecasting in general. Mean average percentage error is around 16%, which is another way for measure forecast accuracy.

In the determination of parameters of ARIMA(p, d, q) model, both endogenous (variables explained by ARIMA model) and exogenous (variables not explained by ARIMA model) variables are used. In the above forecasting implementation, ARIMA model is applied on endogeneous variable only due to memory limitation before assignment submittion.

In the current stage, some existing variables like the text in Marketing, Holiday and Destination Event are not used. They could contain signals in sales forecasting.

In the current stage no feature engineering is applied. As the training data accumulates, variation of date features among months or years can provide signals on forecasting, e.g.:

  • around month end or start people are more likely to consume after salary payment
  • every xmas on Dec 25 the store are closed and hence with no sales (which can also be hard coded)

Currently the economic variables are not considered due to large number of missing values and low correlation with sales. Sometimes economic variables are useful for sales forecasting when their lag values have effects on sales at later time points. This could be further studied in the next trial.

In order to improve forecast, additional features which are not included in the dataset can also be considered, for instance:

  • weather information of individual stores location
  • substitute product information
  • competitor information

4) Scalability & Productization¶

Solution deployment

  • Streamlit In our prototyping in Python and experimentation in scripts, the forecasting model can be quickly deployed with Streamlit as data prototyping application building with user interface.
  • Cloud Cloud services are another alternative, if the underlying computation varies along the day which the cloud services take care with the cluster management.

In order to maintain the model in production so that it is robost to changes in project requirements, the following procedures can be considered:

  • Code Refactoring in modular form Putting code into modular form is easier to maintain, test and debug.
  • Model monitoring Model monitoring is crucial, since there will be data or model drift as time goes, such that the old model is not valid for the upcoming / new data anymore. In this case, model retraining is required and can be scheduled periodically or upon triggers in monitoring.
  • Model training management In case of data size increment due to additional features or training data as time goes, training can be conducted in the cloud with auto-scale cluster management.
